252":"1252","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1271":"1271","Abt 1252":"circa 1252","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","Aft 1271":"na circa 1271","about 1210":"circa 1210","about 1230":"circa 1230","Manor of Croft, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England","Manor of Burton, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England",", Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Easby, North Yorkshire County, England":"Easby, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1210–after 1271":"about 1210–after 1271","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1190–1245":"1190–1245","1190":"1190","after 1271":"after 1271","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1271":"1271","Abt 1252":"about 1252","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","Aft 1271":"after about 1271","about 1210":"about 1210","about 1230":"about 1230","Manor of Croft, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England","Manor of Burton, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England",", Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Easby, North Yorkshire County, England":"Easby, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richmond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Richmond (North Yorkshire). The placename was probably transferred after the Norman Conquest from any of numerous places in France named with Old French <i>riche</i> ‘mighty, strong’ + <i>munt</i>, <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’. Richmond in southwest London received this name only in the reign of Henry VII, in honor of the king, who had been Earl of Richmond until he came to the throne, and is unlikely to be the source of this surname.","occasionally a variant of   Richman  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>. The two names were probably often confused.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Richman","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Richeman</i>, either from an unrecorded Old English <i>Rīcmann</i>, or from a pet form of <i>Richard</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-man</i>. The name was sometimes interchangeable with   Rickman  , especially in recent times.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>riche</i> ‘rich, powerful’ + <i>-man</i>. Compare   Rich  .","English: perhaps a variant of   Richmond  , or vice versa."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old Norse <i>hróðr</i> ‘fame’ + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Alan Roald de Richmond of Burton Manor was born about 1210, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Roald de Richmond, was 47 and his mother, Lady Isabella de Rollo, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Matilda Goldington. He died after 1271, in his hometown, and was buried in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1210–after 1271":"umbes 1210–pärast 1271","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1190–1245":"1190–1245","1190